        body: "Setting a food budget per person per day is the single most effective way to control food costs on a summer trip. For summer 2026, a reasonable travel food budget is $35–$50 per person per day, depending on the destination. Here is how that breaks down. Breakfast ($5–$8): free hotel breakfast is the gold standard, but if your lodging does not offer free breakfast, a grocery-store yogurt parfait and fruit runs $3–$5. A coffee shop breakfast sandwich costs $5–$8. Lunch ($10–$15): food court, food truck, or deli sandwich with a drink. Avoid sit-down lunch at a restaurant with a tip — that is a $18–$25 meal. Dinner ($15–$22): this is where most budget travelers overspend. A sit-down restaurant dinner with a drink and tip runs $25–$40 per person. A grocery store deli hot meal or a food hall stall costs $10–$15. The key: eat two cheap meals and one moderate meal per day. Snacks/drinks ($5–$8): bring your own reusable water bottle (free refills at any Starbucks or fast food restaurant) and buy snacks at grocery stores ($3–$6) instead of tourist shops ($8–$15). The $40/day target is achievable in every U.S. city except New York, San Francisco, and Honolulu — those cities require $50–$60/day to cover realistic costs. For comparison, a family of four eating three restaurant meals per day easily spends $120–$200 per day on food — that is $840–$1,400 for a week. With the budget approach, the same family spends $560–$700. The difference: $280–$700 in savings, which covers a night or two of lodging. For a broader look at how food fits into your overall trip budget, see our [budget road trip planning guide](/articles/budget-road-trip-planning-guide)."
