        body: "Food halls and public markets are the budget traveler's greatest ally in any U.S. city. They combine variety — so picky eaters and adventurous diners can both be happy — with competitive pricing, since multiple vendors compete for the same customers. Top food halls across America: Ponce City Market (Atlanta), Chelsea Market (NYC), Reading Terminal Market (Philadelphia), Pike Place Market (Seattle), Grand Central Market (Los Angeles), and Revival Food Hall (Chicago). At any of these, you can eat a full meal for $10–$15, compared to $20–$35 at a comparable sit-down restaurant. The second strategy is food trucks. Cities with legendary food truck scenes: Austin (over 1,200 active food trucks), Los Angeles (the taco truck scene is arguably the best in the country), Portland (the food cart pod system), and Denver (a thriving food truck scene with a city permit system that encourages variety). Food truck meals average $8–$14 — about 40% less than a brick-and-mortar restaurant for similar quality. The third strategy is ethnic grocery stores and their prepared food sections. H-Mart (Korean grocery chain with locations in major cities), 99 Ranch Market (Chinese), and Patel Brothers (Indian) have hot food bars and deli counters where you can eat a substantial meal for $5–$10. Most offer free rice with hot food purchases. For a deeper look at how food prices vary by region, the Eater (eater.com) Heatmap series tracks the best cheap eats in every major U.S. city, updated monthly."
