        body: "Summer is the best season for budget eating in America because the produce is abundant, local, and cheap. Farmers' markets hit peak supply from June through September, and prices drop accordingly. A basket of peaches in Georgia ($4–$6 for a half-bushel), sweet corn in the Midwest ($2 for a dozen ears), tomatoes in New Jersey ($3–$4 per pound), and berries in California ($3–$5 per pint) are all at their seasonal cheapest. Eating seasonally saves money and elevates your food quality simultaneously. Practical tips for seasonal eating on a road trip: (1) Visit the local farmers' market in every city you pass through — the USDA National Farmers Market Directory lists over 8,000 markets nationwide. Arrive 30 minutes before closing for the best deals (vendors discount produce to avoid hauling it back). (2) Build meals around what is in season: instead of buying expensive imported produce at a grocery store, buy what local farms are overflowing with. (3) U-Pick farms: many farms let you pick your own berries, peaches, apples, or vegetables for $2–$5 per pound — 30–50% cheaper than store prices, and a fun family activity. U-pick season runs June through September across most of the country. (4) Roadside farm stands: especially in New England, the South, and the West Coast, roadside stands offer the freshest produce at farm-direct prices. Honesty-box stands (leave cash, take produce) are common in rural areas and are always the cheapest option. The bonus: eating fresh, local produce is healthier than fast food, keeps your energy up for hiking and activities, and gives you a genuine taste of each region you visit. For more on building a trip around food experiences without overspending, check our cheap US destinations guide — several cities on that list are also among America's best food cities.",
