        heading: "Trip Cancellation vs Trip Interruption vs Cancel for Any Reason: The Key Terms",
        body: "Understanding these three terms is critical before buying any policy. Trip Cancellation insurance covers you if you need to cancel your trip before departure due to a covered reason — typically illness, injury, death of a family member, severe weather, or a terrorist incident in your destination city. Covered reasons are explicitly listed in the policy and vary by provider. Trip Interruption insurance covers you if you need to cut your trip short after departure for a covered reason — for example, a family emergency that requires you to fly home, or a hurricane that forces an evacuation. It typically reimburses the unused portion of your trip plus the cost of your last-minute return transportation. Cancel for Any Reason (CFAR) is an upgrade available on most comprehensive policies. It typically costs 40–70% more than a standard policy but allows you to cancel for any reason not listed as a covered reason — changing your mind, fear of travel, or even a work conflict. CFAR usually reimburses 50–75% of your non-refundable trip costs, compared to 100% for standard trip cancellation. The key trade-off: CFAR gives you flexibility at a higher price, and you typically must purchase it within 14–21 days of making your first trip payment. For summer 2026 specifically, CFAR is worth serious consideration given the unpredictable market environment.",
